entry.title: Windows sandbox: Split TransferVariable address param into local and
entry.content:
remote parts



This change enables concurrent use of TransferVariable by splitting the

address param into local and target parts. This allows the broker to

copy data from a local variable instead of from the global variable.

This works because the broker only needs the address of a global

variable in its own process for determining the corresponding address

in the target, and so it is not required for any data to be set in the

broker-side global before copying.

entry.title: [SavedTabGroups] Add browser command to launch tutorial from What's New
entry.content:
Add browser command for Saved Tab Groups tutorial



Adding a browser command to be triggered from the whats new page.

This command will start the Saved Tab Groups tutorial. This should

only execute if the #tab-groups-save feature flag is enabled.



To locally test:

- Build patch and run Chrome (branded build) with the feature flag

enabled (#tab-groups-save).

- Navigate to chrome://whats-new, open devtools in iframe, and run:



Note: Make sure devtools are not detached in a different window. This

affects how the tutorial finds the first anchor element.



window.top.postMessage(

{'data': {'commandId': 11, 'clickInfo': {}}},

'chrome://whats-new'

);



The implementation of this tutorial can be found here:

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/5174237

entry.title: Fix mojoString16ToString to support very large byte sequences
entry.content:
This fixes a crash that occurs when mojoString16ToString() is passed a

very long string. Because the implementation uses the spread operator,

this would cause very many arguments to be passed to

String.fromCharCode() and surpass the max call stack size.



This was causing crashes on the chrome://downloads page because the

display URL string could be very large.



This is fixed by converting the mojo string in chunks, so that each call

to String.fromCharCode() does not have too many arguments. This

implementation is adapted from the Closure library and uses the same

chunk size:

https://github.com/google/closure-library/blob/7818ff7dc0b53555a7fb3c3427e6761e88bde3a2/closure/goog/crypt/crypt.js#L104-L123

entry.title: infra: Remove ungardened child testers from mega cq
entry.content:
Suppose there's a parent builder and a child tester. If the parent is on

a gardener rotation and the child is not, any mirroring trybot of the

child gets added to the mega CQ. This is unfortunate because any

such trybots are likely very red and unstable/unusable due to the

mirrored CI bot not being monitored. eg: This is such a bot:

https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/chromium/builders/try/android-webview-12-x64-dbg



So this changes how bots are added to the mega CQ to exclude these

bots. Note that before we were iterating through CI builders ->

get their trybots -> add or skip those trybots. Now we reverse it

so that we iterate through trybots -> get their mirrored CI bots ->

add the trybots based on aspects of the CI bots. This is so we can

get the set of all garden rotations for mirrored CI bots.



As an example, this ends up removing the bot:

https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/chromium/builders/try/mac_chromium_dbg_ng



This mirrors the two bots:

https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/chromium/builders/ci/Mac%20Builder%20%28dbg%29

https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/chromium/builders/ci/Mac13%20Tests%20%28dbg%29



The first one is gardened while the second one isn't. So it correctly

gets removed. While a bot that mirrors _only_ the former remains on

the mega CQ, which is also correct:

https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/chromium/builders/try/mac_chromium_compile_dbg_ng

> > > The most popular arm64 builds (Trichrome) are shipping with

> > > is_high_end_android. The Monochrome arm64 builds are shipped for old

> > > devices, and we expect these to gradually become less popular.

> > >

> > > This change sets is_high_end_android to true for arm64 builds by

> > > default.

> > >

> > > This would make local benchmarking slightly less error prone because

> > > there would be a little less to remember to set in GN args when making a

> > > build for the most popular official configuration.

> > >

> > > Known effects:

> > >

> > > 1. Seemingly all official arm64 builders now explicitly set

> > > is_high_end_android. Hence no effect for them.

> > >

> > > 2. Non-official arm64 builders will change to become high-end, even the

> > > ones that end up running on old devices (example: android-arm64-rel).

> > > In this patch we make sure that is_high_end_android is ignored for

> > > non-official builds (disabled RELR relocations for non-official).

> > > Hence, no effect here as well.

> > > 3. Official builds of Monochrome made by devs would fail to run on

> > > Android pre-P (because RELR support is lacking). This leads to

> > > mysterious crashes during something-dlopen in the Android dynamic

entry.title: [UPMLocalSettings] Introduce second password check
entry.content:
There will be 2 password checks in the safety check UI:

- The check for passwords stored in the local storage

- The check for passwords stored in the account storage (meaning that

those passwords sync across user devices)



Both checks will be displayed only if sync is on and the

upm-local-no-migration feature flag is enabled.



For each of the checks the corresponding password check model is

created in the coordinator, mPasswordCheckLocalModel and

mPasswordCheckAccountModel. Any of the models can be null (e. g. if

sync is off mPasswordCheckAccountModel is null; if sync is on but

upm-local-no-migration flag is disabled mPasswordCheckLocalModel is

null).



P. S. Right now both password checks have the title "Passwords" and are

impossible to distinguish. The account storage title will be changed in

a follow-up CL to "Passwords saved on ".
